  "prompt": "Can I write improvements with supplementary exams in intermediate 1 year?",
  "response": "The ability to write improvement exams depends on the educational board or institution governing your intermediate (or high school) education and their specific policies.\n\nIn many educational systems, students are given the option to improve their scores by taking supplementary or improvement exams. Here\u2019s what you might typically expect:\n\n1. **Policy for Improvement Exams**: Most boards allow students who are dissatisfied with their marks to register for improvement exams. These exams are intended to give students a second chance to enhance their scores.\n\n2. **Registration and Fees**: You will usually need to formally register for these exams and pay a fee. The registration process might involve filling out forms and submitting them before a specified deadline.\n\n3. **Subjects**: You might be allowed to choose the subjects in which you want to improve your scores. Each board has its own rules regarding the number of subjects you can opt for improvement.\n\n4. **Result Impact**: The marks obtained in improvement exams usually replace the original marks if they are higher. However, specific policies might vary, such as whether the highest score or the most recent score is considered.\n\n5. **Timing**: Improvement exams are typically held after regular exams, and the schedule for these exams is usually announced well in advance.\n\nTo get accurate information pertaining to your situation, you should:\n\n- Check with your school or educational institution.\n- Review the guidelines provided by your specific educational board.\n- Visit the official website of your educational board for detailed instructions and timelines.\n\nEnsure that you understand all the deadlines and requirements to take full advantage of the opportunity to improve your scores.",
